column14: S/B RAMP FROM IH-45S TO IH-610
column168: Carrier vehicle northbound on IH45 and entered ramp to IH-610E at an unsafe speed. Centrifigual force caused the tractor trailer to strike the left barrier wall. The tractor jacknifed to the left and the trailer overturned to the right. The unit then slid partially onto teh grass median between the ramp and the main lanes of IH-610E.  The fifteen totes were secured to prevent lateral motion but during the overturn all were scattered from the center of the trailer forward. Three totes were crushed and leaked contents.  The others were damaged but not leaking.  Contents of non-leaking totes were pumped into clean totes transported to the scene.  Soil from the spill area and all fifteen of the now empty totes were removed for proper disposal. Storm drain was cleaned.
column169: Retrain drivers on the physics involved with curves and the proper way to negotiate curves and ramps.

column62: Impact with Sharp or Protruding Object (e.g., nails)
column168: The contents of a box truck were being transferred to a van trailer at the Truck to Truck facility.  A drum on a drum dolly was punctured when the dolly hit a bump, causing approximately 4 gallons of material to spill onto the trailer floor before it was uprighted.  The employees notified their supervisor and donned the appropriate PPE.  Absorbent pads were placed around the spill.  The spill was contained prior to any material leaking onto the ground.  The damaged drum and absorbent pads were placed into a salvage drum and the trailer was cleaned with a suitable cleaning material.  The salvage drum was then loaded onto the trailer to be transported to the intended waste disposal facility.
column169: All truck loading employees were cautioned to use proper care when loading drums from one trailer to another and be vigilant for bumps that can cause drums to slip off of the drum dolly.

The local fire dept. arrived along with an emergency response team.  The agencies decided to let the fire burn itself out.

column168: While unloading a 20 cubic yard rolloff container at the 10 day transfer facility yard, approximately 25 gallons of material spilled over the rear top door under the tarp onto the ground.  The facility's emergency response crew was notified immediately.  They donned the appropriate PPE and contained the material on the concrete pad with a suitable absorbent material.  The area was cleaned up and the spilled material was placed into another rolloff container, where it was then disposed of at the intended waste disposal facility.
column169: In order to prevent a recirrence, the driver has been instructed to inspect each container and ensure that the container is loaded in such a way that wen the roll-off container is either loaded or unloaded from the roll-off frame that the material cannot escape from the container while the roll-off tarp is in place.

column42: LIGHTER REFILLS CONTAINING FLAMMABLE GAS NOT EXCEEDING 4 FLUID OUNCES (7.22 CUBIC INCHES) AND 65 GRAMS OF FLAMMABLE GAS
column168: Shipper had tendered container, SEAU172398-6/ANC090276, to Horizon Lines in Anchorage on 12/14/08, to go on the Horizon Tacoma, TW738S for transit to Kodiak. During a random inspection it was discovered that there was a UN1057/Class 2.1 that was non-declared and incompatiable with  UN1223/Class 3, UN1090/Class 3, UN1263/Class 3, UN3066/Class 8, UN2796/Class 8,UN1993/Class 3, and UN 1133/Class 3. Shipper was notified and the UN1057/Class 2.1 was removed at their request so container could proceed properly. UN1057/Class 2.1 returned to shipper.
column169: Shipper must review all shipments to make sure loaded material is reflected properly on the paperwork and every commodity is compatiable with one another, prior to tendering to the trucker and the ocean carrier.

column168: The tanker was being loaded at the customer's site by the driver who was wearing the appropriate PPE.  At the conclusion of the loading, while putting away the hoses, the driver noticed material leaking from the bottom of the trailer.  The shipper's technician and the driver quickly placed a bucket and absorbent pads under the trailer at the point of the leaks.  The driver vented the tank to releive the pressure but it had little effect.  The driver notified his supervisor, and two trucks were dispatched to the site in order to transfer the load.  Upon arrival, the replacement trailer was spotted and all required operational and safety controls were estabished in order to transfer the load onto the new trailer.  The transfer was conducted without issue.  Once empties, the original trailer was placed out of service and transported to a repair facility for inspection.  Upon inspection, it was determined that 2 wleds had failed allwing the material to escape from the trailer.  This trailer is currently out of service pending repairs.
column169: Prior to dispatch of the vehicle, the driver confirmed that the trailer was current with all required inspections and the pre-trip inspection performed did not identify any signs of damage or leaking.  Upon indentifcation of the leak, the driver took all appropriate actions to safely contain the release and initiate an appropriate emergency response to prevent an escalation of the incident.  Drivers will continue to inspecte each container and vehiucle priopr to use and/or acceptance and take those actions necessary in the event a damaged or leaking package is identified.

column168: On December 11, 2008, the Veolia office in Blaine, MN received a phone call notifying them of a green liquid dripping out of the back of a Veolia truck while traveling on the public roadway. The Veolia office immediately contacted the driver of the truck who then pulled off the road and assessed the situation. The driver discovered an IBC (tote) was leaking hydrochloric acid solution. With the help of another Veolia technician, the spill in the truck was contained with oil dry and absorbent pads, and the crew returned to the Veolia, Blaine field office. It appears that the tote shifted sideways while in transit, made contact with the handle of a drum cart which resulted in a puncture to the plastic tote. It was estimated that approximately 75 gallons of material spilled out of the tote while the truck was in motion.
column169: As a result of this incident, the requirement to properly block and brace all cargo to prevent and movement relative to the transport vehicle was reviewed with all field and transportation employees. Specifically ways to ensure adequate lateral bracing were reviewed.

column168: 12/12/2008: During a routine inspection at Conrail's Linden, NJ railyard, FRA Hazardous Materials Inspector R.A. Dedow noted a drip originating from the top rim of the bottom outlet valve 4" closure cap of tank car NATX 37197, load Ethanol; shipped from Sasol N.A., Wilmington, NC, to Sasol Chemicals N.A., c/o Kinder Morgan Bulk Terminals, Carteret, NJ, at a rate of 1 drop every 10-15 seconds.  Product was evaporating upon contact with the ground.    CR Risk Mgr. A.Richter contacted emergency response contractor REACT, who examined the rail car to confirm the leak.  A small bucket with chemical absorbant pads was affixed to the bottom outlet valve for further work to be accomplished the following day.    12/13/08: REACT and CR Richter examined the outlet, insuring the valve and other closures were secured, then slowly removed the closure cap, whereby eventually approximately 2 pints of material were released into the previously placed containment system.  It was noted that the bottom outlet closure cap gasket was deformed due to age.  Gasket replaced in kind (Viton), and cap and closure plug resecured tool tight.  Outlet was re-examined approximately 1 hour later, with no further release noted.  Car was okayed for transportation to original consignee.
column169: No additional comments.

column168: There were 34, 55 gal Drums and two totes on this shipment. This was a shipper load and count shipment from 081 to 165. It went out for delivery on the same trailer it was picked up on. When loaded in Tulsa, OK there apparently was a piece of wood appox 18 inches long with a nail stuck through it laying on the floor of the trailer. When the drums were loaded one drum was pushed up against the nail with enough force to puncture the drum. The nail apparently stayed inbedded in the drum until the drum was moved at the final destination and the resin started to come out. There was one drum refused for the puncture and six other drums that got resin on the bottom from the leaking drum.~~NOTE: the package identification markings were not recorded by the terminal for this report.
column169: Hazmat team cleaned the six contaminated drums and secured the damage drum in recovery drum. ~~The trailer was cleaned prior to loading but after the trailer was loaded, the shipper discovered that all the freight was not going to fit properly so some of the freight was then removed at which time a piece of a pallet must have broke off leaving the piece of wood with nails in the trailer. Not all the freight was removed so the wood was not seen. When the trailer was being reloaded and the skids of drums were being maneuvered into the trailer with a forklift, the piece of wood with the protruding nails punctured into a drum causing this spill.

column168: Driver is directed by a consignee employee at to where to unload and into what   storage tank. The driver had paperwork that requires the customer representative to  sign prior to off-loading that states that their storage tank has the capacity to hold the shipment. The driver's responsibility during the off-loading is with the vehicle. The consignee employee's responsibility is to monitor the storage tank level.  The storage tank is out of the drivers view so when the tank level gets to a critical point the employee is to signal to the driver to stop the off-load.  The tank overflowed because the consignee employee assigned to monitor their storage tank left the area. Liquid level in the storage tank raised to a critical point and because air pressure is used to unload the tank trailer some of that pressure pushed the level even higher and some material vented out of the tank into a containment area. The material was cleaned up by plant employees.
column169: In this instance, the driver was doing everything he was supposed to. The Consignee employee left his post allowing their tank to overfill. If the monitor of the tank needs to leave and there is no backup person or automated device to shut down when levels in the tank become critical then the driver should be directed to shut down the product transfer until such monitoring can be restored.

column168: On 12/3/2008 at 07:59, personnel in the CSXT Manville Yard discovered GATX 72728, a loaded tank car of Hydrochloric Acid, with a vapor leak from the top of the car. The car was isolated and the shipper and consignee were notified. Reagent Chemical sent a represenative to inspect the tank car. It was discovered that there was no frangiable disk in the pressure relief device. Reagent found an approximate 3" rubber "O" in its place. Reagent placed a new 165lb Zouk disk on the car. At this time the vapor leak was secured and the car was released for transporation.    No Special movement was needed and No AAR 7.1 is required on this release.  Cause Code: 437  NARRI: 5 (5+5+0) X (2+2) = 200
column169: No additional comments.

column168: On 12/05/2008 at 13:10, personnel in the CSXT rail yard in Selkirk, NY discovered UTLX 210184, a loaded  tank car of Alcohols N.O.S., leaking from the top of the car. The CSXT General Car Foreman responded and found the liquid valve open and the liquid valve plug was not tool tight. The General Car Foreman tightened the valve plug and stopped the release. Miller Environmental, a CSXT response contractor was dispatched to the scene to clean up the spilled material and to verify the liquid line valve was in the closed position and the valve plug was installed correctly.  The shipper was notified directly of the incident. The leak was secured and the car released for transport.     Note: This incident did not require a special shipping move.    Cause Code: 119  NARRI:  5 (5+3+0) x (2+0) = 80
column169: No additional comments.

column168: While at the Veolia ten-day in-transit facility in Menomonee Falls, WI, a 220 gallon IBC or tote was being transferred from one trailer to another. Prior to moving the tote,  a Veolia employee noticed that there was some material that was spilled onto the floor of the trailer. Upon further investigation, it was discovered that the tote had a small (<2 inch) crack on the top "shoulder" of the tote. It was estimated that approximately 2 gallons of material, waste fuel oil and PCB's, was released onto the trailer floor. The Veolia employee then proceeded to clean up the spilled material and transfer the contents of the tote to another IBC tote. The emptied tote along with the spill clean up debris were shipped for disposal at the Veolia hazardous waste incinerator located in Port Arthur, TX.
column169: This incident will be reveiwed with field and transportation employees to remind them to verify container integrity at every opportunity. column168: A van trailer was being moved from the 10 day storage yard to the intended waste disposal facility.  When opening the doors, the driver noticed a strong smell and notified his supervisor. The material was cleaned up and placed back into the pail where the lid was resecured and the material sent for disposal at the intended waste management facility.

On December 10th at 13:25 in the CSXT Davis Yard, FRA Inspector David Snyder discovered UTLX201549, a tank car of Flammable Liquid, N.O.S. releasing product from top of car.  The car was isolated and Chemtrec (report number 2008121000151) assisted in contacting the shipper, Ticona Company.  The consignee, Invista SARL, was requested to assist and found the liquid line valve closure plug less than tool tight with the valve in the closed position.  Invista representatives removed the closure plug, wrapped the threads with teflon tape, then re-installed and properly tightened the plug with a wrench.  Ticona representative Terreca Purdy was informed that due to the defective valve they must obtain an FRA Movement Approval prior to the car being released to destination.  Approximately 10 gallons was released from the container.    This incident did not require a special movment.   An AAR 7.1 Quality Assurance form will be completed.     Cause Code: 120  NARRI: 5 (5+3+0) x (2+0) = 80.

column168: On December 12, 2008 at 01:25, personnel in the CSXT East Side Yard (RG) discovered UTLX 200539, a loaded tank car of Hydrogen Peroxide, leaking from the top of the car and a member of the crew was sprayed with a small amount of product. The crew member rinsed off and no medical treatment was needed. The car was isolated and the shipper, PA DEP and Chemtrec were notified (CHEMTREC Report# 2008121300007). React, a CSXT response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the frangible disk was ruptured. Contractor personnel replaced frangible disk, decontaminated the car and cleaned up spilled material. The leak was secured and the car released for transport.     This incident did not require a special switching move and no AAR 7.1 is required.    Cause Code: 441  NARRI: 2 (5+5+0) x (2+2) = 80
column169: No additional comments.

column168: On December 15, 2008 at 14:30, personnel in the CSXT Cumberland Yard were advised from an FRA Inspector that UTLX 201944, a loaded tank car of Isopropenylbenzene, was leaking from the vacuum relief device. The car was isolated and the shipper was notified via Chemtrec (Report#2008121500101). Specialized Professional Services was contacted by Sunoco and dispatched to inspect the car. SPSI removed the vacuum relief device and placed a plug in its place until another device could be installed. On December 17, 2008 SPSI, a certified Class "G" facility, replaced the device and performed a bubble leak test on the car. The car was deemed by SPSI to be released for transport.     This incident did not require a special switching move and No AAR 7.1 is needed.    Cause Code: 466  NARRI:  2 (5+3+0) X (2+0) = 32
column169: No additional comments.

column168: Damaged freight was discovered in the nose of trailer when it was being unloaded.  When discovered, the weight of all drums had crushed the pallet it was shipped on.  When the drums were removed from broken pallet it was found that two of the drums had the bottoms punctured by nails from the crushed pallet. It was hard to tell when the pallet crushed or when the nails punctured the bottom of drums. There were small nail holes in bottom of the two drums.
column169: The shipper needs to ensure that the pallets the product is being shipped on can withstand the weight of the productand the effects that transportation will have on them.

column168: On Quality Distribution Claim 23991, a Quality Carriers was observed with product leaking on its exterior skin. Some of the spent acid dripped onto a police car and some material impacted the pavement. An  environmental contractor was dispatched to the site. The released material was neutralized and absorbed.  Recovery materials were containerized for transportation and disposal.

On December 24th at approximately 1400 hours a Trimac Transportation truck was driving within the IMTT Bayonne terminal and heading to the East scale/gate when an IMTT Security employee noticed the Trimac driver get out of his vehicle to check his wash out caps on top of the tank trailer.  When the IMTT Security employee approached the truck he noticed that product had spilled from the top of the tanker and along the side.  The Security employee contacted his supervisor and gave notice to the East gate that the vehicle not be allowed to exit the terminal.  As the truck proceeded to the East gate, product continued to spill out of the top of the tanker and onto the roadway.  The truck was held at the East gate and IMTT Emergency Response personnel arrived to survey the situation.  A strong solvent odor was detected.  IMTT contacted the on site emergency response contractor to dispatch to the area to clean up the tank trailer and the spilled product around the scale area.  The driver was asked to check his wash out caps and when he removed one them the gasket was found to be cracked and separated.  The driver replaced the gaskets on both wash caps and after the clean up operation the truck was permitted to proceed out of the terminal.  An IMTT vehicle escorted the truck out of the East gate and onto a main road to make sure that no additional product leaked from the truck.  No further incindent was reported.
column169: It is the responsibility of the truck driver to secure his load before leaving IMTT property.  This includes checking gasket seals.

column168: Under Quality Distribution Claim 23972, it was reported that material was observed leaking from the cargo tanker onto its exterior shell and subsequently onto the  pavement area. An environmental contractor was dispatched to the site. All loose product was scraped up and containerized for transportation and disposal. The tanker was then taken to a truck wash where the remaining viscous material was subsequently removed.

On 12/26/08 at approximately 1050 hours a Linden Bulk Transportation truck was receiving a load of 7500 gallons Methy alcohol (methanol) at IMTT-Bayonne.  The truck had approximately 3,000 gallons of methanol loaded when a leak was detected at a pipeline connection under the tank trailer.  The operation was shut down and a 5-gallon pail was placed under the pipe to contain the dripping product. The truck was moved to a secured containment area and arrangements were made to have another truck brought to the area and transfer the product from the leaking trailer to the empty one.  The second trailer was then brought back to the loading rack and the operation resumed without further incident.  At the time of the incident it was determined that the leak occurred at the threads connecting the piping to a valve under the tank trailer.
column169: IMTT-Bayonne contacted the customer of the product to inform them of the incident.  The customer subesquently contacted the transportation company and will address any mechanical or structural issues with the truck and related components to prevent recurrences.

column169: Plant personnel and driver should have verified that the vent was actually open before the transfer took place.

column168: In the process of doing routine maintenance of cleaning a strainer screen in the vapor eliminator the mechanic closed the air operated belly valve.  He then loosened four nuts that held the plate in front of the screen in order to vent off propane gas in the line between the belly valve and the screen.  The belly valve air actuator piston did not travel its full travel so the belly valve was not really shut. As gas continued to   leak out he tried to close an auxiliary ball valve.  The handle turned but it did not shut off the flow. He tried to tighten the four nuts on the plate but an o ring had popped out of its seat. Finally the belly valve was manually closed by repeatedly striking on its external operating lever.
column169: We have changed our operating procedure on how to determine when the belly valve is closed. Instead of a visual check, we will hook up the delivery hose to the tank and pump through the meter. We will then shut the valve and if the meter stops we will know the valve is truly off.  We will also only vent off vapor by loosening a fitting on top of the vapor eliminator instead of the bolts that hold the plate.   We will flare off (torch) gas whenever possible.

column168: On 12/20/08 at 00:30, personnel in the CSXT Russell KY rail yard discovered PROX 44202, a loaded tank car of Gasoline, leaking from the top of the rail car when moved. The rail car was isolated shipper was notified via CHEMTREC (report number #200812200005). A CSXT response contractor was sent to the rail yard and discovered that four (4) of the hinged bolts used to secure the manway were less than tool tight. The contractor tightened the four bolts and checked the other four for tightness and released the car for shipment.        A special switching move was required   An AAR 7.1 form was not completed        NARRI :  5 (5+3+0) * (2+0) = 80  Cause Code = 200

column168: Driver was eastbound on E1560 when he approached a sharp curve.  As the driver enter the curve he realized his trailer was offtracking to far to the left into the oncoming traffic lane.  At the same time, the driver reported an oncoming car. The driver attempted to quickly steer to the right to get back in his lane and then back left to stay on the road when he lost control.  The trailer's momentum and high center of gravity carried the transport over on its side and onto the northbound shoulder. The Driver climbed out of cab and contacted Supervisor to report the incident. The Supervisor notified OKDPS who responded to the scene. The product on the overturned transport was transferred to another transport truck safely with no loss.  A 3rd party wrecker service uprighted the overturned transport and towed to repair facilities.  No product was lost due to the incident.
column169: Share accident investigation and findings with other drivers.  Express the importance of driving according to conditions in addition to observing speed limit postings.  Recognize when fog conditions become unsafe for a driver to operate a transport and find a safe place to pull over until the fog lifts.  Promote safe driving at all times.

column62: Loose Closure, Component, or Device; Human Error
column168: Driver unload to customers storage tank using tractor mounted product pump.  Driver used a 3x2 inch adaptor coupling with a 3/4 inch blow down ball type valve.  The valve had a locking device to prevent the valve from accidental opening.  The adaptor was mounted in line on the pump 3" discharge piping than a 2" product hose was coupled to the adaptor.   While unloading, the ball valve on the adaptor viborated open which allowed product to leak out. Driver recognized the problem and shut and secured the ball valve. Driver than shut down the product transfer and and with the help of the customer's operator, cleaned up the spilled material. Driver replaced the fitting and continued with product delivery without further incident.
column169: Upon inspection of the fitting in question it was found that the there were two problems involving the blow down ball valve mounted on the fitting.  The first issue was the locking device. it was damaged which through viboration allowed it to slip back on the handle of the valve. second, the valve itself was  loose due to use.  Both together allowed the valve to viborate open.  The other issue was with the driver, he did not recognize the problems with the valve in the first place. If he did, he would have used another fitting and had the bad fitting placed out of service until it could be repaired. The driver has been retrained per company policy and the fitting has been repaired and placed back into service.

column168: Maersk tendered their customer's container, TTNU242340-0/554952002, to Horizon Lines in Hong Kong on 12/14/08 for transit to Tacoma. The Horizon Hunter, HU020E, noticed on 12/25/08 that a material was leaking from the container. It was determined that the liquid was UN3265, and vessel took appropiate action to contain. Notification was made to Maersk for their addressing on arrival in Tacoma, Wa on 12/26/08. A clean-up vendor was employed so that clean-up was completed on the vessel and the container was addressed to prevent any leakage during the discharge operation. Maersk took possession of the container in Tacoma for corrective action.
column169: The container was full of double stacked plastic totes in aluminum framed baskets containing UN3265.  From the pictures that were taken, it seems apparent that the totes were not made to be stacked, since there are no landing pads/slots at the top of the tote basket to receive the upper tote. The upper tote rested on the tote below and pictures show the upper tote's weight depressed the lower tote. In this settling the lower totes frame distorted forcing metal members into the plastic tote penetrating it.   To prevent similar type issues, these totes need to be single stack and properly blocked and braced to prevent movement with the dynamic forces of an ocean crossing.

column168: Florida Rock & Tank Lines, Inc. driver loading his truck at Nustar's loading rack at the valero terminal. The driver opened all 5 belly valves, put in scully cord and then hooked the vapor connections. The driver bucket drained and then checked for the gas light. The driver then connected hose 1 to compartment #5, 2500 regular. Hooked hose 2 to compartment #1, 3000 regular. Hooked diesel head to compartment #2. Compartment 5 finished loading but diesel kept starting and stopping. Diesel finally started to flow continuously but at 831 gallons the gas began to leak out of the top of the compartment. Driver immediately hit the stop button but approximately 200 gallons had leaked into concete area. No fuel reached soil or drains. The site was cleaned up by the onsite operator and supervisor on duty.
column169: The incident was reviewed on video by Nustar management and it was determined that the driver following all proper loading procedures. The previous drivers readings were all evaluated and compared the this driver and again it was determined that the driver had done all properly. Nustar's investigation concluded that the rather than 1300 gallons of diesel to be loaded the meter attempted to load 1500 gallons. Nustar has corrected the faulty meter and site has been inspected by internal Safety Supervisor.

column168: Shipment 831-635350 arrived at the Conway Portland facility after being picked up from the customer.  At 19:45 pm on 12/10/08 Employee Bryan Karalas was unloading the trailer and moving the freight to the proper outbound loading doors.  He entered the trailer that contained shipment 831-635350 and picked up the pallet that had been loaded immediately behind.  He failed to judge his forklift blade distance and proceeded forward too far to where his forkblades protruded beyond the end of the pallet he was picking up and into the bottom of the 55 gallon drum.  The contents of the drum spilled onto the trailer floor and concrete pad beneath the trailer.  The spill containment kit was utilized to lay out barriers to prevent the spread of the spill, and the dock was evacuated as a precautionary measure.  Belfor Environmental was contacted for further instructions and advised to remain 300 feet off the dock until they arrived to the scene.  Belfor cleaned up the spill and trailer on site.  Conway Manager of Safety Jeff Turner was also immediately notified of the spill.
column169: The spill resulted from an employee failing to take the required precautions with respect to correct forklift procedures.  The employee received written disciplinary action, will be retrained in forklift safety and recertified on a forklift prior to being permitted to operate a forklift.  He will also watch a loading & unloading techniques video (I.C.E.) and will complete a written quiz.  The employee has also been counselled regarding his actions which led to the spill.

column168: Upon opening the trailer door it was found that multiple bags of copper sulfate crystals had ruptured and released approximately 15 lbs. of material onto the trailer floor.  ERTS then dispatched Earth Movers Environmental to the site for cleanup activities.  The damaged bags and released material were containerized into drums for disposal.

According to the information obtained, the following occurred.  Upon inspection of the trailer, at the Bridge Terminal Transport, Inc. facility in Jacksonville, Florida, a leak was discovered.  Free product had leaked from the back of the trailer onto the soil/gravel surface beneath the trailer.  Area was isolated.  Southern Waste Services of Jacksonville, Florida was dispatched to perform the cleanup.  Upon arrival on site, Southern Waste Services began to hand shovel the affected soil/gravel mixture beneath the trailer.  Southern Waste Services proceeded to inspect the trailer, and discovered one (1) 300-gallon tote had been crushed by heavy freight.  Approximately 2 gallons of free product had released from the damaged tote.  Southern Waste Services offloaded the trailer, neutralized the free product, and cleaned the trailer floor.  Trailer was reloaded.  Damaged tote was offloaded into four (4) 85-gallon drums, and spent absorbents and contaminated gravel were placed into five (5) 55-gallon drums.  Disposal will be coordinated in accordance with local, state, and federal regulations. There were no injuries or exposures reported.
column169: Since the release was accidental, and appears to be related to crushed freight, no plans currently exist to prevent recurrence.  Maersk Lines and Bridge Terminal Transport, Inc. will continue to train and reinforce safe handling procedures to all personnel.

column168: An outbound drayage driver presented paperwork for the release of a 20 foot intermodal tank container TCVU 241746 at the BNSF intermodal facility out-gate. The driver's Dispatch Ticket and Drayage Instructions indicated that the commodity shipped in TCVU 241746 was a hazardous material [Combustible Liquid, NOS (2-Cyanopyridine) NA 1993, PG III]. TCVU 241746 was an import shipment that BNSF received for rail movement at the Port of LA and had previously arrived on a BNSF inbound train without incident. The billing that BNSF received indicated that 2-Cyanopyridine was IMDG non-hazardous; therefore no hazardous billing was associated with this shipment from Los Angeles, CA to Houston, TX. BNSF updated the billing information for TCVU 241746 to coincide with the drayage driver's paperwork and afterwards TCVU 241746 was out-gated.

column168: A BNSF switch crew reported ACFX 71656 (DOT 111A100W1 tank car) leaking product from the top fitting area in the railyard. Nearby BNSF contract hazardous material responders were called and inspected ACFX 71656. The inspection revealed that the sample line pipe extension below the valve body was broken off at its connection into the pressure plate. The responders applied a plug into the open sample line orifice which closed and secured the open orifice. All other valves and fittings were inspected and found secure. All spillage evaporated. Securement was completed at 2120 hrs. CST, 12/14/08.
column169: No additional comments.

column168: TILX 190685 (DOT 111A100W1 tank car) was reported leaking product from the manway area during normal switching activities in the railyard. Switching movement was stopped and a BNSF hazardous material responder was called. The BNSF Assistant Director of Hazardous Material responded and inspected TILX 190685. All manway securement bolts were found to be tool tight. The manway cover was opened to inspect the condition of the manway gasket. The manway gasket was found pinched which prevented a good seal. The responder replaced the gasket with a new manway gasket and resecured the manway cover. All spillage that didn't evaporate was wiped. Response was concluded at 1330 hrs. CST, 12/19/08.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column169: DUNNAGE BETWEEN OR LIGHTER FREIGHT ON TOP.  PROPER LOADING TECHNIQUES MUST BE FOLLOWED EACH TIME WHEN LOADING PAILS OF LIQUIDS, CHEMICALS AND HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.  PAILS, CYLINDERS, BAGS AND DRUMS OF CHEMICALS MUST BE COMPLETELY SHROUDED USING DUNNAGE, PLYWOOD AND OR MTY PALLETS.  WHEN HANDLING AND MOVING PAILS AND DRUMS, KNOW THE SURROUNDINGS TO ENSURE PRODUCT IS NOT EASILY DAMAGED.  PLACE CUSHION BETWEEN ROWS AND LAYERS OF CHEMICALS TO PREVENT OTHER OR ADJACENT FREIGHT TO EASILY DAMAGED.  TRAINING IN WORK METHODS ON PROPER AND SAFE LOADING OF CHEMICALS.  RECURRENT TRAINING IN HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.  WHEN LOADING NOTE THAT BAGS, PAILS OR DRUMS OF LIQUIDS AHEAD.  HEAVY FREIGHT LOADED ON THE BOTTOM, LIGHT FREIGHT ON TOP!  USE PLENTY OF CUSHIONING BETWEEN LAYERS OF FREIGHT.  DO NOT LOAD HEAVY FREIGHT ON TOP OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.

column168: On December 10, 2008 at 0930 personnel in the CSXT Howell Yard in Evansville, Indiana near Ohio and 10th street, discovered CMHX247003, a loaded covered hopper car of Ammonium Nitrate leaking from bottom unloading gates.  The car was isolated and shipper, local, and state agencies as applicable were notified. CHEMTREC Report #2008-12-10-00081.  Summit Contracting, a CSXT response contractor, was dispatched to the scene.  The car was moved to the mechanical department where it was noted that 3 of the 4 bottom unloading gates were allowing the product to leak.  Seals were intact on operating fixtures but the ratchet closures were not tight enough and the mechanical department was able to properly secure the openings.  Contractor personnel cleaned up spilled material and loaded into three 55 gallon drums with an estimated weight of 400 pounds each.  The leak was secured and the car released for transport.  This incident did require a special switching move

column168: While moving the electric pallet jack, our driver caused the blade to hit a drum on an adjacent pallet and put a 6” slit in the bottom of the drum.  The product was COR69-AB-861W – ODD LOT RESIN.    Immediate Action Taken:   Our driver rolled the drum on its side keeping the slit facing up.  He then called Kathleen and they agreed to take the following actions:      ¿  Spread a plastic sheet on the ground at the rear of the van trailer.  ¿  Put an empty tote tank on the plastic sheet.  ¿  Move the drum to the end of the trailer while the slit opening was still facing up.  ¿  Have an employee of Tec Composites use the forks of their lift to cradle the drum and lift it up past the level of an empty tote tank.  ¿  Open the bung of the drum and drain the product into the tote tank.  ¿  Apply and secure the bung to the drum.  ¿  Secure the empty drum to the side of the trailer to keep it from moving.   ¿  Close the opening of the tote tank, put it in the van trailer, and secure it.  ¿  Change the bills of lading for both the delivery of the drum and the return of the partially filled tote to facilitate return of the material to NAC in Lakeland.    ¿  Remove the spilled product on the floor of the trailer by spreading absorbent over the spilled product and picking it up with a shovel.  ¿  Put the cleanup material (product and absorbent) into an empty 5-gallon pail.    ¿  Re-clean the floor of the trailer with detergent and allow it to dry.    ¿  Sell the salvage product that was transferred to the empty tote tank.     Future Corrective Actions:  Our driver should have been more careful as he maneuver the electric pallet jack inside the trailer.  A written disciplinary action memorandum is warranted and issued.

Yard operations were suspended accordingly. Responder inspection of AGCX 10036 revealed product staining around the manway nozzle and down both sides of the side shell. No active release was noted at this time. Two manway securement lug nuts were found to be less than tool tight. The manway gasket was inspected along with the product outage and both were deemed OK. The manway cover was closed and properly resecured. All other valves and fittings were inspected with no exceptions noted. Spillage on the tank shell evaporated and ground impact spillage was treated with an application of MicroBlaze. Yard operations resumed at 2225 hrs. CST, 12/26/08.    On 12/29/08, the responders returned and pressured up AGCX 10036 with insertion of nitrogen into this tank car. This pressure test revealed product leaking from the liquid line valve's mounting flange area. The mounting flange bolts were less than tool tight and the responder tool tightened these flange bolts and afterwards no further product leaks were noted. No other leaks were detected. Another application of MicroBlaze was applied to the ground impact area of the 12/26/08 spill and the ballast/soil was churned to expedite the microbial penetration and its' effectiveness.  AGCX 10036's side specification stencil indicated that the last tank qualification was completed in the year 2006 and next due in 2016.

Quality Carriers trailer #7282 was initially rejected by the destination facility on Dec. 3, 2008 due to not meeting profile parameters because of low flashpoint as described on a separate Hazardous Materials Incident Report.  Upon arrival at the GE Betz, Orange, TX facility, representative samples of the waste water were collected from the top and bottom of the trailer and submitted to a NELAP-accredited lab for flashpoint analysis.  Initial written results indicated that the flashpoints of the samples were greater than 200 degrees Fahrenheit confirming that the wastewater was not a hazardous material and that it was within the waste profile parameters.  Based upon this information, GE Betz reshipped the wastewater in trailer #7282 on Dec. 5, 2008 to the destination facility in Baton Rouge, LA as a "Non DOT Regulated" wastewater.                While the trailer was in route to the destination facility, the laboratory contacted GE Betz and stated that the written preliminary results were inaccurate and that the wastewater actually exhibited a flashpoint of 153 degrees Fahrenheit.  GE Betz contacted Quality Carriers dispatch and instructed to Quality Carriers to redirect trailer #7282 back to the GE Betz facility in Orange, TX.                          The wastewater was subsequently classified and shipped as a Combustible Material N.O.S. (Naphthalene Solution), NA1993, PG III.
column169: The facility has improved operating procedures, training, and waste shipment procedures to prevent future occurrence. Procedure changes were communicated to applicable facility personnel.                                                      The facility has implemented a semiannual cleaning procedure of the wastewater storage tank to prevent the accumulation of an organic or bi-layering of the wastewater in the storage tank.  Operators have been trained and the importance of facility waste management techniques and waste segregation were stressed.  All laboratory quality assurance/quality control (QA/QC) reports will be reviewed in the future to confirm accuracy of preliminary reports prior to hazardous materials classification.

Quality Carriers trailer #7282 was loaded with non-RCRA hazardous, process wastewater generated at the GE Betz Facility in Orange, TX.  At the time of shipment, the wastewater did not meet the definition of hazardous material.  The loaded trailer departed for Baton Rouge, LA on the evening of Tuesday, Dec. 2, 2008 as a "Non-DOT Regulated" material.  The trailer was staged at a Quality Carrier yard overnight and arrived at the destination facility the next morning.  On Wednesday, Dec. 3, 2008, a sample of wastewater from trailer #7282 was collected and analyzed for disposal purposes by the destination facility.  The analytical results indicated a flashpoint outside of the wastewater profile parameters causing the load to be rejected by the treatment facility.  The destination facility contacted GE Betz on Wednesday, Dec. 3, 2008 to request that the rejected load be removed from the destination facility.  Trailer #7282 was then transported from the destination facility back to the GE Betz facility in Orange, TX and arrived on the evening of Wednesday, Dec. 3, 2008.      Additional analytical testing conducted by GE Betz contracted third-party laboratory confirmed that the material in trailer #7282 underwent a phase separation after it was shipped from the GE Betz facility that caused a thin layer of material in the storage trailer to exhibit the hazardous material characteristic of combustibility (flash point of 153 degrees Fahrenheit).  The proper shipping name of the resultant wastewater was Combustible Material N.O.S. (Naphthalene Solution), NA 1993, PG III.  During this incident, there were no package failures, injuries, or releases of hazardous material.
column169: The facility has improved operating procedures, training, and waste shipment procedures to prevent future occurrence.  Modification to waste shipment procedures include a 1-hour pre-departure tanker truck holding time and sampling of the top and bottom layer of the tanker to help ensure material stratification within the tanker has not occurred.  Procedure changes were communicated to applicable facility personnel.  The facility has implemented a semiannual cleaning procedure of the wastewater storage tank to prevent the accumulation of an organic or bi-layering of the wastewater in the storage tank. Operators have been trained and the importance of facility waste management techniques and waste segregation were stressed.  All laboratory quality assurance/quality control (QA/QC) reports will be reviewed in the future to confirm accuracy of preliminary reports prior to hazardous materials classification.

The trailer arrived at the destination facility that afternoon and a sample of wastewater from the trailer was collectedand analyzed for disposal purposes by the destination facility.  The analytical results indicated a pH outside of the wastewater profile parameters causing the load to be rejected by the treatment facility.  The destination facility contacted GE Betz on Friday, Dec. 5, 2008 to request that the rejected load be removed from the destination facility.  Trailer #70943 was then transported from the destination facility back to the GE Betz facility in Orange, TX and arrived that evening. While switching in the railyard, the crew on a BNSF road switcher reported a foul chemical odor smelling similar to rotting cabbage [a methyl mercaptan odor] emanating from a nearby yard track. This crew moved away from the odor source area and yard operations were ceased. The local F.D. and EMT's were called. The EMT's examined two crew members at the railyard facility finding no inhalation or medical issues with these two employees and they were able to return to work. A BNSF hazardous material response contractor was called to inspect suspect tank cars and eliminate the odor source. Responder inspection revealed PSPX 22145 (DOT 105J500W tank car) as the odor source. Intact seal numbered CPC 242041 was removed from the valve housing cover. The A-end liquid valve was found to be leaking from around its' valve stem area. Responders attempted to tighten the valve stem packing nut, but liquid product escaped when the packing nut was tightened. The packing nut was removed from the stem along with the locking ring and spacer ring. The locking ring appeared slightly bent which likely attributed to binding on the valve stem and asserting uneven pressure on the stem packing when the packing nut was tightened, allowing a small amount of liquid product to seep out. A Midland capping kit was ordered to encapsulate the leaking liquid valve. PSPX 22145 was carefully moved and isolated in a siding just outside the railyard and air monitoring was initiated while responders awaited the arrival of the capping kit. Yard operations were resumed at 1300 hrs. CST, 12/21/08. After the Midland capping kit arrived around 1400 hrs. CST, the responders again attempted to repair the leak location at the liquid valve stem. Additional packing material was inserted and the imperfect locking ring was removed. Afterwards, the packing nut was tightened and no visible leaks were noted. The valve was cycled and no leakage was detected. Spillage within the valve housing area was cleaned. The valve housing cover was resealed with seal numbered SRS 000266. Response was concluded at 1630 hrs. CST, 12/21/08.   PSPX 22145 was returned to the shipper.  PSPX 22145's side specification stencil indicated that the last tank qualification was completed in the year 2007 and next due in 2017.

column169: BOXES CONTAINING FIRE EXTINGUISHERS AND OTHER CHEMICALS MUST BE COMPLETELY SHROUDED USING MTY PALLETS, PLYWOOD AND/OR DUNNAGE.  IT IS VERY IMPORTANT TO MAKE SURE THE BOXES ARE SECURED AND TIGHT TO PREVENT SHIFTING AND CARTONS FALLING. USING DECK BARS OR LOAD LOCK BARS PROPERLY AND SAFELY TO LOAD FREIGHT ON TOP OF!  RETRAINING IN WORK METHODS ON PROPER AND SAFE LOADING OF CHEMICALS.  RETRAIN IN WORK METHODS ON PROPER STACKING AND LOADING OF FREIGHT, INCLUDING HAZARDOUS MATERIALS AND CHEMICAL SHIPMENTS.  HEAVY FREIGHT LOADED ON THE BOTTOM, LIGHT FREIGHT ON TOP!  USE PLENTY OF CUSHIONING BETWEEN LAYERS OF FREIGHT.

column168: When a driver was getting ready to go out on his daily pick up and delivery run he went over to his trailer that had just been loaded that was still backed into the dock to check out his load. No known action was discovered that contributed to this unintentional release. We are not sure if it was hit by other freight, dropped, etc. - we just could not figure it out. Spilled material was neutralized and cleaned with absorbent and placed into a recovery container as was the cracked container.

column168: Auto collision, Other vehicle travels left of center on a two lane, two way state highway striking our vehicle left front to left front.  Impact damage tears drivers side fuel tank, mounted on frame of tractor from mounting brackets, punctures, tears, and gashes fuel tank, repeatedly.  Damaged fuel tank immediately losses entire amount of fuel (approx. 100 gal.) as it spins to rest, post collision. Passenger side fuel tank also damaged, however remains attached to tractor frame and losses approx. 100 gal. over the next hour.  Our tractor-trailer traveled off the roadway & remained upright, the other vehicle post collision, traveled off of the roadway and rolled onto the drivers side.  The driver of other vehicle was the fatality victim.  No loss of produce from DOT 306 fuel transport trailer being pulled.  Clean-up and remediation by Basin Environmental services, OKC, Ok.
column169: No improper act by our driver.  Other vehicle traveles left of center, collides with our vehicle- two-way state highway curved, level, roadway no obstructions No loss of product from loaded DOT 306 fuel transport trailer. Trimac driver unloaded his first stop at Newburyport, MA and was traveling north on Interstate 95 for 23miles when he heard a popping sound and pulled unit to shoulder of interstate at marker 10.  When driver walk to rear of trailer driver saw fire coming from the brake area on driver side of unit, driver returned to cab to get his fire extinguisher to put fire out.  Driver could not stop the fire so he called 911 for help.  Greenland Volunteer Fire Department and the NH State Police responded to scene.  Fire Chief Ralph Cresta ordered the highway closed and the surrounding homes evacuated because of unknown hazards.  After the fire was out the homes were allowed back, which was less than 30 minutes time. The roadway was closed for 90 minutes to insure everything was cleaned from roadway and re-opened.                                                                             Trailer was towed to National Wrecker Service, which is located at Portsmouth, NH.  Contact Ralph Cresta.

column168: (A)A BNSF westbound train derailed 37 railcars on BNSF main track. The cause of this derailment was attributed to a broken rail at a field weld. The derailed railcars included eleven hazardous material tank cars (one load and 10 residues). UTLX 202192 (DOT 111A100W1 tank car) derailed in a pile and came to rest upside down. A fire ensued fueled by releasing methanol from the vacuum relief valve (VRV) and a small hole on the    A-end tank head near the 9 o'clock position. UTLX 202192 was up-righted in a position which ended further product release at the VRV and from the hole in the tank head. The fire was then extinguished. Also, after up-righting UTLX 202192, a small product leak developed at the bottom outlet area as the bottom outlet valve was sheared off in the derailment. This spillage was contained and captured. The remaining product inside UTLX 202192 was transferred in tank trucks for delivery to the consignee. Captured spillage atop the ground along with a mix of fire retardant foam and water was placed into portable totes for future disposal.  UTLX 202192 was deemed destroyed and it was cleaned and purged of all hazardous material.  (B)A BNSF westbound train derailed 37 railcars on BNSF main track. The cause of this derailment was attributed to a broken rail at a field weld. The derailed railcars included eleven hazardous material tank cars (one load and 10 residues). UTLX 204090 (DOT 111A100W1 tank car) derailed in a pile and came to rest on its side. UTLX 204090 sustained a small gash type hole toward the bottom of tank near the B-end. Residue product vapors that were ignited by a nearby burning methanol tank car burned inside UTLX 204090. The fire was extinguished. UTLX 204090 was deemed destroyed and it was cleaned and purged of all hazardous material.  (C)A BNSF westbound train derailed 37 railcars on BNSF main track. The cause of this derailment was attributed to a broken rail at a field weld. The derailed railcars included eleven hazardous material tank cars (one load and 10 residues). TEAX 3405 (DOT 105J300W tank car) derailed in a pile and came to rest on its side. TEAX 3405 sustained a small gash type hole on its' left side shell. Residue product vapors that were ignited by a nearby burning methanol tank car burned inside TEAX 3405. The fire was extinguished and afterwards, any remaining residue propane inside TEAX 3405 was flared-off. TEAX 3405 was cleaned and purged of all hazardous material.  (D)A BNSF westbound train derailed 37 railcars on BNSF main track. The cause of this derailment was attributed to a broken rail at a field weld. The derailed railcars included eleven hazardous material tank cars (one load and 10 residues). SHPX 221737 (DOT 112J340W tank car) derailed in a pile and came to rest upright atop another derailed tank car. SHPX 221737 sustained a crack/split in its' side shell. Any residue propane that remained inside SHPX 221737 was flared-off. SHPX 221737 was deemed destroyed and it was cleaned and purged o
column169: No additional comments.

The derailed railcars included eleven hazardous material tank cars (one load and 10 residues). UTLX 202192 (DOT 111A100W1 tank car) derailed in a pile and came to rest upside down. A fire ensued fueled by releasing methanol from the vacuum relief valve (VRV) and a small hole on the    A-end tank head near the 9 o'clock position. UTLX 202192 was up-righted in a position which ended further product release at the VRV and from the hole in the tank head. The fire was then extinguished. Also, after up-righting UTLX 202192, a small product leak developed at the bottom outlet area as the bottom outlet valve was sheared off in the derailment. This spillage was contained and captured. The remaining product inside UTLX 202192 was transferred in tank trucks for delivery to the consignee. Captured spillage atop the ground along with a mix of fire retardant foam and water was placed into portable totes for future disposal.  UTLX 202192 was deemed destroyed and it was cleaned and purged of all hazardous material.  (B)A BNSF westbound train derailed 37 railcars on BNSF main track. The cause of this derailment was attributed to a broken rail at a field weld. The derailed railcars included eleven hazardous material tank cars (one load and 10 residues). UTLX 204090 (DOT 111A100W1 tank car) derailed in a pile and came to rest on its side. UTLX 204090 sustained a small gash type hole toward the bottom of tank near the B-end. Residue product vapors that were ignited by a nearby burning methanol tank car burned inside UTLX 204090. The fire was extinguished. UTLX 204090 was deemed destroyed and it was cleaned and purged of all hazardous material.  (C)A BNSF westbound train derailed 37 railcars on BNSF main track. The cause of this derailment was attributed to a broken rail at a field weld. The derailed railcars included eleven hazardous material tank cars (one load and 10 residues). TEAX 3405 (DOT 105J300W tank car) derailed in a pile and came to rest on its side. TEAX 3405 sustained a small gash type hole on its' left side shell. Residue product vapors that were ignited by a nearby burning methanol tank car burned inside TEAX 3405. The fire was extinguished and afterwards, any remaining residue propane inside TEAX 3405 was flared-off. TEAX 3405 was cleaned and purged of all hazardous material.  (D)A BNSF westbound train derailed 37 railcars on BNSF main track. The cause of this derailment was attributed to a broken rail at a field weld. The derailed railcars included eleven hazardous material tank cars (one load and 10 residues). SHPX 221737 (DOT 112J340W tank car) derailed in a pile and came to rest upright atop another derailed tank car. SHPX 221737 sustained a crack/split in its' side shell. Any residue propane that remained inside SHPX 221737 was flared-off. SHPX 221737 was deemed destroyed and it was cleaned and purged o

column168: FREIGHT HANDLER ATTEMPTING TO CROSS THE DOCK WITH A PALLET ON HIS FORKLIFT BLADES RAN THE CORNER OF THE PALLET HE WAS MOVING INTO A STAGED PALLET OF PAINT, DENTING AND CAUSING ONE, ONE GALLON CAN OF PAINT TO LEAK A HALF GALLON TO THE DOCK.  HE THEN NOTIFIED HIS SUPERVISOR OF THE LEAK AND ONCE GIVEN PERMISSION, DONNED PERSOANL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT GLOVES AND A FACE SHIELD, THEN PLACED THE DAMAGED PRODUCT INTO A CONTAINMENT DRUM AND CLEANED UP THE AREA.
column169: MINIMIZE THE STAGING OF HAZARDOUS MATERIAL AND IF IT MUST BE STAGED IT SHOULD BE PROTECTED WITH PLYWOOD AT ALL TIMES.  ALL EMPLOYEES MUST BE AWARE OF THEIR SURROUNDINGS AND UTILIZE EXTRA CAUTION WHEN WORKING AROUND HAZARDOUS MATERIAL.

column62: Human Error; Inadequate Blocking and Bracing
column168: WHILE UNLOADING TRAILER AT RENTON, WA CON-WAY DOCK ON 12/14/2008 AT 1620, A CON-WAY DOCKWORKER NOTICED A LEAKAGE STAIN ON CARTON CONTAINING TWO ONE-GALLON CANS OF PAINT-RELATED MATERIAL.  HE NOTIFIED THE OPERATIONS MANAGER ON DUTY WHO LOOKED AT THE SHIPMENT, DETERMINED A ONE-GALLON CAN HAD BEEN SLIGHTLY CRUSHED ON TOP DUE TO IMPROPER BLOCKING PROTECTION, CAUSING THE CAN TO BUCKLE AND A SMALL HOLE TO DEVELOP.  APPROXIMATELY ONE CUP OF CONTENTS LEAKED ONTO THE CARTON.  THE ONE-GALLON CAN WAS REMOVED AND PROPERLY CONTAINED AT RESTON DOCK IN A PAIL WITH A LID PLACED SECURELY ON IT.  THE REST OF THE SHIPMENT WAS DEEMED OK FOR TRANSPORTATION ON TO THE NORTH PORTLAND CON-WAY SERVICE CENTER.                                          THE SPILL WAS IMMEDIATELY CLEANED UP, SO THERE WAS NO FURTHER RELEASE AND NO RELEASE ONTO THE TRAILER FLOOR.
column169: Additional training and discipline will be given to the loader in Cincinnati, OH Con-way Service Center.  Proper blocking and bracing protection of the shipment will be the topic of training.

column168: DURING THE TWILIGHT SORT OPERATIONS EMPLOYEES NOTICED SMOKE COMING FROM A PACKAGE.  RESPONSE AND INVESTIGATION SHOWED THAT THE CONTENTS OF THE PACKAGE INCLUDED TWO DE650S NONSPILLABLE LEAD-ACID BATTERIES, WHICH HAD BEEN PLACED TOGETHER WITH 5 OTHER SMALL ITEMS INSIDE A METAL CAGE AND THEN INSIDE A FIBERBOARD BOX.  AS THEY WERE LOOSE INSIDE THE CAGE, THE BATTERIES APPEARED TO HAVE MOVED FREELY ENOUGH TO DISLODGE CAPS OVER THE SPRING-TYPE LANTERN TERMINALS AT THE TOP OF EITHER ONE OR BOTH BATTERIES.  IN TURN, THE TERMINALS SHORT-CIRCUITED ACROSS THE METAL BARS OF THE CAGE.  AT LEAST ONE OF THE BATTERIES HEATED SUFFICIENTLY TO MELT THE EXTERIOR BATTERY CASE.  THE SMOKE GENERATED BY THE SHORT-CIRCUIT COATED THE INSIDE OF THE PACKAGE BUT DID NOT CAUSE A FIRE.
column169: SHIPPERS OF BATTERIES MUST PROVIDE POSITIVE MEANS TO PREVENT CONTACT BETWEEN TERMINALS AND ANY ITEMS THAT COULD POTENTIALLY CAUSE A SHORT-CIRCUIT.  TRAINING SHOULD ALSO  ADDRESS REQUIRED PACKAGE MARKINGS.

column168: One skid tied to the side of the trailer. As a result of the last skid hitting the glass bottles, one bottle inside the carton broke while the trailer was in transit. column169: In this case our driver tied a piece of freight to the wall of the trailer. By friction the rope was cut from another piece of freight moving into the rope. The delivery driver saw what was happening and re-tied the rope and added a load bar to keep freight from moving. The tied freight then tipped in another direction causing the chain reaction and then damage to the glass bottle. This has been brought up in the Safety Meeting and employees were explained in this case the freight should have been loaded in a different part of the trailer.

column168: The drums were tendered on 2 Shrink Wrapped Pallets. Freight shifted off pallets during transit. 6 plastic, 15 gallon drums, fell over. 2 of the drums leaked a small amount of Corrosive Liquid out of the Vent Caps. I estimate less than2 ounces of product leaked.Upon discovery of leak. Unloading was halted, Safety Department was called. I spoke with Jeff Turner, he instructed me to call the Shippers Emergency number.Chemtrec was called, I spoke with Abraham. He instructed me it was safe to clean-up spill with Proper PPE: RubberGloves, Face Shield. Spilled material could be cleaned with Absorbent. Leaking drums were placed in plastic lined overpack containers, to be shipped back to point of origin as per Shippers Instructions with Chemtrec.Clean-up was completed by Jimmie Morris Driver-Pasco, WA

column168: The Driver failed to disconnect the hose after making a delivery to a stationary tank.  The employee was done filling the tank and the customer approached the employee to verify the driver filled the tank only to the amount they desired.    Due to the distraction, the Driver omitted to do a walk around of the vehicle and left the hose attached to the stationary tank. The driver started the vehicle and pulled away without detaching the hose. Upon pulling away, the driver immediately realized he had not detached the hose and stopped the vehicle. There was a dispersion of 8 vapor gallons from the hose that quickly dissipated in the air.  There were no injuries and no property damage.
column169: Employees are coached to follow our policies of performing a complete walk around of the vehicle before moving it.  Employees who fail to follow our policies are often times required to write and present a safety meeting to their peers covering the infraction they committed.  A pull-away is regarded as a very serious offense, therefore have a greater potential for more severe disciplinary actions.

The package is a set of shelves with non-spillable batteries on each of three shelves.  There were 20 total 12-volt batteries in the package.  As the system was being moved via forlift, the forklift hit a bump causing the top heavy system to fall forward and hit the ground.  Each of the 20 batteries was connected together.  None of the batterys' terminals were protected from short circuiting. When the batteries shifted, the terminals came in contact with the metal shelving causing them to arc.  The system caught fire numerous times.  The fire was extinguished & the system was ultimately righted.  The batteries were disconnected & are being held in the Memphis Hub pending disposition.  FAA Special Agent Ken Holman was notified & responded to the scene. The system was marked per USG-11.

column168: During the twilight sort operations, employees noticed fire involving a package on a conveyor belt within the Little Rock hub. Sprinklers in the facility were activated by the fire and UPS management called 911. All employees were evacuated at 21:45 hrs. The fire department responded and extinguished the fire. Employees returned to work at 23:15 hours, 90 minutes after evacuating. Investigation after the fire was extinguished led to discovery of the remnants of several aerosol cans, which had burst in the heat of the fire. The configuration of several similar shipments of aerosols led to the determination that the remnants were associated with several intact packages being shipped between the shipper and consignee listed above in this report.
column169: Damage to one or more aerosols appears to have released the propellant, a mixture of Dimethyl ether and 1,1,1 ,2-Tetrafluoroethane. The propellant, in turn, could have been ignited by static electricity. Since the cause of the damage to the aerosols is unclear, it is difficult to make any recommendations to prevent future occurrences.

column168: Driver was loaded at Honeywell in Baton Rouge, La.  Driver is not involved in loading process; Honeywell employees load truck and seal dome. Driver left facility and drove down Chippawa St.  He noticed product spilling onto Chippawa St. approximately 1/4 mile long.  The product also pooled where the truck was stopped.  The external valve handle indicated to be in the closed postion.  A cap was not covering the end of the unload hose.  This would have prevented product release even though the valve was stuck open.  US Environmental was called to the scene and cleaned up the spill. The truck and trailer were then driven back to Honeywell and a new external valve was installed on the trailer.  The load was then delivered to its destination.  The tank had been recently tested.  The tests performed and dates are as follows:           V 09-08, I 10-08, K 10-08, L 10-08, P 10-08, UC 0-08, & T 12-08.
column169: Basically, the spill occurred as a result of mechanical failure of an air actuated external valve.  Pressure built up in the tank causing product to flow into the unload hose through the defective valve.  A cap should have been placed on the unload hose end.  This would have kept product from spilling into the environment during transportation, but the driver would have been splashed when the cap was removed from the hose to unload product.  In the future, we will train our employees to make sure the air actuated valves are in the closed position and hoses are capped prior to movement on the highway.

column169: Employees are coached to follow our policies of ignition key control and performing a complete walk around of the vehicle before moving it. column168: MY DRIVER RAN ONTO THE SHOULDER OF HWY 903 OUTSIDE OF LANCASTER, SC.  THE SHOULDER WAS VERY NARROW AND THE DEEP OFF WAS STEEP.  HHE WAS NOT ABLE TO PULL THE TRUCK BACK ONTO THE ROAD AND IT WENT DOWN THE EMBANKMENT.  THE TRUCK AND TRAILOR TURNED OVER AND COMPLETELY BUEVED UP.  MY DRIVER WAS ABLE TO ESCAPE WITHOUT INJURY.  THE ACCIDENT OCCURED AROUND 1340.  THE LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT, EMS, AND POLICE RESPONDED.  MY DRIVER CALLED ME ABOUT 1405. I CALLED MY ENVIRONMENTAL COMPANY, ENVIRONMENTAL HYDROGEOLOGICAL CONSULTANTS, INC,.  THEY CALLED DHEC OF SC AND NOTIFIED THEM.  I LEFT IMMEDIATELY AND ARROVED AT THE SCENE ABOUT 1530.  THE TRUCK AND TRAILOR HAD COMPLETELY BURNED UP BY THE TIME I ARRIVED.  THERE WAS NO WAY TO TELL WHERE THE TANK FAILED  THERE WAS NOTHING LEFT OF THE TANK OR TRUCK EXCEPT THE FRAME AND AXLES, AND SCRAP METAL MOST OF THE PRODUCT BURNED HOWEVER A SMALL AMOUNT WAS RELEASED.  THOMAS AMMRUP FROM EHC, INC ARRIVED ABOUT 1645 .  HIS CREW ARRIVED SHORTLY AFTER HIM.  THEY RECOVERED ABOUT 2000 GALLONS OF A MIXTURE OF WATER, GASOLINE & DIESEL.  THOMAS ESTIMATED THAT IT WAS ABOUT 400 GALLON OF PRODUCT AND THE REST WATER FROM THE FIRE DEPARTMENT.  HE RETURNED ON THE 24TH AND CHECKED THE SITE.  ON THE 30TH EHC DUG OUT AND REPLACED ABOUT 200 TONS OF DIRT.

column169: AFTER EXTENSIVE INVESTIGATION OF ALL DATA AVAILABLE OUR ROOT CAUSE TEAM WITH ARCO BP WAS NOT ABLE TO COME UP WITH A TRUE ROOT CAUSE OR CRITICAL FACTOR THAT CAUSED THIS EVENT.  OUR INVESTIGATIVE TEAM REVIEWED THE ON BOARD COMPUTER SYSTEM DATA, PHOTOS AT THE SCENE, MAINTENANCE RECORDS, VIDEO FOOTAGE OF THE DRIVER LOADING, HOURS OF SERVICE, ROAD CONDITIONS, AND WEATHER.  AFTER A 3 DAY INVESTIGATIVE PROCESS AND A GREAT DEAL OF DATA WE WERE UNABLE TO COME UP WITH A LOGICAL ROOT CAUSE FOR THIS EVENT.  AS A RESULT NO RECOMMENDATIONS HAVE BEEN MADE AT THIS POINT.

column168: 1) PETROLEUM EXPRESS NC. ACCIDENT REPORT  2) HOUSTON POLICE DEPARTMENT CP# 0265076  3) DIAGRAM OF ACCIDENT  4) RESPONSE REPORT    Petroleum Express Inc. Accident Report   Date: December 6, 2008   Written by: Peggy Roark   On December 6, 2008 one of our transport trucks turned over at the intersection of   Beltway 8 and S. Post Oak. The driver, Carl Dunlap reported that he stopped at the red light at the intersection of Beltway 8 and S. Post Oak, after the light turned green, he moved from the left lane to the right lane and continued through the intersection, to make the curve he swung wide and made a buttonhole turn. As he was straightening the   vehicle out, the load shifted and the truck and trailer rolled over. See Diagram of   accident. The driver got out of the truck uninjured and there was no other vehicle or persons involved in the accident. The Houston Police Department DOT responded to the accident and the driver was not sited for the accident. The Report number is CP# 0265076 and a copy is attached. The driver was tested that evening for drugs and   alcohol and the reports came back clean.   The truck was carrying 8501 gallons of gasoline. There was spill of 1590 gallons of unleaded gasoline. The remainder of the fuel was pumped out of the overturned truck and taken to another fueling location. There was a small rupture in the bottom of the trailer in compartment 1. The truck remained on its side which placed the rupture near the top of the tank, which limited the amount of fuel lost. The total gallons lost were 1590 gallons. All the lost fuel went into a storm drain that was located near the overturned truck.   Garner Environmental Services was hired to investigate and remediate the lost fuel. Garner Environmental Services was retained to handle the clean up. I am attaching a copy of the Response Report from Garner Environmental which reports the spill to be complete.   Garner Environmental contact person is John Pavlicek 713-817-1395. Dennis Alverez with the City of Houston was present. Mr. Alverez was on site the night of the accident and on the subsequent trip to remove the fuel from the storm drain. Mr. Alverez can be reached at: Office 713-293-2069 or Cell 713-293-2069. I can be reached at 713-223- 0231.   Peggy Roark   President   Petroleum Express Inc., 2661 Stevens Street #2, Houston, Texas 77026   March 27, 2009

DIRECT FROM DRIVER REPORT (FILED 12/30/08 4 P.M.):DRIVER WAS HEADED UP PEPPER RD (CHELSEA, VT) TO ACCT 94938, INDIVIDUALS NOT A COMPANY. THERE WAS NO VISIBLE SAND ON ROAD-AS GOT CLOSE TO TOP OF HILL. REAR LOCK WAS ENGAGED AND BOTH REAR WHEELS BEGAN TO SPIN.TRUCK STARTED TO SLIDE BACKWARDS, I PUT THE TRUCK IN REVERSE TO REGAIN CONTROL OF REAR WHEELS AND TRIED TO STEER TO OPPOSITE SIDE OF ROAD WHERE DITCH WAS LESS DEEP. COULD NOT, NO RESPONSE, SLIDING FASTER AND FASTER.SLID OFF ROAD AND TRUCK TURNED ON SIDE AWAY FROM PEPPER RD. INTO BROOK.  WHEN TRUCK CAME TO REST AND I REGAINED MY BEARINGS--BLEEDING PRETTY BAD FROM CUT ON HEAD--EXITTED THROUGH DRIVER DOOR (WHICH WAS ABOVE ME), CLIMBED DOWN FROM FRAME, SHUT OFF EMERGENCY VALVE, DID NOTICE SOME VAPOR LEAKING. CLIMBED BANK TO PEPPER ROAD AND FLAGGED DOWN A VEHICLE.  WAS BROUGHT TO CHELSEA HEALTH CENTER AND TREATED (2 STITCHES TO BROW)ASKED NURSE TO CONTACT MY EMPLOYER, LEONARD'S GAS & ELECTRIC, WHICH THEY DID APROX. 11:30 A.M.    FROM OPERATIONS MANAGER ANDY STEWART:    RECIEVED A CALL FROM CHELSEA HEALTH CENTER APROX. 11:30 A.M. 12/30/08 INFORMING ME THAT MY DRIVER, SHANE WEST, WAS INVOLVED IN AN ACCIDENT ON PEPPER ROAD IN CHELSEA AND WAS BEING TREATED FOR MINOR SCALP INJURY AND TRUCK WAS OFF THE ROAD-IMMEDIATELY LOCATED DISTRICT MANAGER MICHAEL SCHMELL, WHO ALONG WITH SERVICE MANAGER ROBERT MUNUKKA RESPONDED TO CHELSEA IMMEDIATELY ARRIVING APROX. 12:30 P.M.. I CALLED TMC EMERGENCY RESPONSE COMPANY (1-800-223-8865)AND ASKED THEM TO RESPOND-CALLED 911 AND SPOKE WITH CHELSEA FIRE DISPATCH WHO ADVISED THAT EMERGENCY RESPONSE, ORANGE COUNTY SHERIFF, AND CHELSEA FIRE DEPTS. HAD ALL RESPONDED. REPORTED SPILL TO VT HAZMAT (WHO SENT 3 TEAMS TO SCENE), WHO WAS IN CONTACT WITH MYSELF AND SEAN @ TMC THROUGHOUT INCIDENT. BNR WRECKING, FROM LEBANON, NH WAS ALSO CONTACTED AND DISPATCHED.    @ APROX. 1:30 PM--DRIVER, TECH, AND BOBTAIL TRUCK WERE DISPATCHED FROM LEOANARD'S WOODSTOCK FACILITY WITH PUMP-OFF EQUIPMENT. DAMAGED TRUCK WAS LOCATED ON DRIVER'S SIDE DOOR FACING NORTH AT BOTTOM OF A 15-25 FOOT HOLE IN BROOK RUNNING PARALLEL TO PEPPER RD. SEVERAL ATTEMPTS WERE MADE TO CONTAIN LEAK, (CRUSHED PIPING AS A RESULT OF IMPACT OF REAR AND BROOK BOTTOM)AND SECONDARY WRECKER SERVICE (SABIL & SONS-WHITE RIVER JUNCTION VERMONT)COMBINED EFFORTS WITH BNR TO LIFT VEHICLE BACK ON TO ROAD--AS VEHICLE FRONT TIRES REACHED NEAR SHOULDER OF PEPPER ROAD--PIPING RELEASED LARGE FLOW OF LIQUID PROPANE. (APROX. 2300 GAL) DECISION WAS MADE BUT VT HAZMAT TO LEAVE TRUCK IN CURRENT POSITION (WRECKERS STILL HOOKED BUT NOT ATTEMPTING TO FURTHER REMOVE VEHICLE FROM BROOK)AND EVACUATE SOME 19 RESIDENCES DOWN STREAM AS WELL AS STAFF ON SIGHT. TRUCK CONTINUED TO EVACUATE OVERNIGHT, MONITORED BY HAZMAT AND DISTRICT MANAGER. NO DIESEL OR MOTOR FUEL WAS DETECTED AND FUEL TANKS/OIL PAN WERE NOT DAMAGED. IN EARLY HOURS OF THE MORNING (12/31/08) ICE PATCH AND LOW TEMPS COMBINED TO STABLIZE LEAK ENOUGH TO FINISH EXTRACTING TRUCK AND MOVING TO LEVEL G

column168: International Package with an invoice that was blacked out information by the customer. We were rewraping the package because it got damp due to the rain. When we opened the package we found restricted products inside. Merchandise is 2 - boxes with complete skin care products inside. When we called the help desk they informed us that these whould have been marked at least ORMD. Additionally the invoice states that they were shipping shoes.

column168: The plastic IBC tote bottom had a 6 inch crack in it from what appears to be fatigue.  Not possible for a forklift puncture due to the positioning of the crack.  M. Ludzy of XBD was the last person to handle the freight.  The freight was not touched after leaving the origin.  Trailer 313-6157 was cleaned out by First Response and is ready to be re-used.  The spilled product has been recouped into two fifty-five gallon salvage drums and taken by First Response. Photographs are on file.  Cleanup started at 315am and the response team finished at approximately 11am.
column169: Original shipper notified and subrogation has started.  Recommend to the shipper that additional testing to the IBC's (totes) should be done.

column168: The package was dropped in handling.  Examination of the inner container revealed a ruptured seam which allowed the contents to escape. The leakage was contained.  The undamaged portion of the package was repacked for return to shipper.
